ieldwork, this richly detailed study of Mekeo esoteric knowledge, cosmology, and self-conceptualizations recasts accepted notions about magic and selfhood. Drawing on accounts by Mekeo ritual experts and laypersons, this is the first book to demonstrate magic's profound role in creating the self. It also argues convincingly that dream reporting provides a natural context for self-reflection. In presenting its data, the book develops the concept of "autonomous imagination" into a new theoretical framework for exploring subjective imagery processes across cultures.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDreams. 0aEthnopsychologyxPapua New Guinea. 0aEthnopsychologyzPapua New Guinea. 0aMagic, Mekeo. 0aMekeo (Papua New Guinean people)xPsychology. 0aMekeo (Papua New Guinean people)xRites and ceremonies. 0aPhilosophy, Mekeo. 0aSelf (Philosophy)xPapua New Guinea. 0aSelf (Philosophy)zPapua New Guinea. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aanthropology.  aautonomous imagination.  acomparative religion.  acosmology.  acultural studies.  adream reporting.  adreams.  aesoteric knowledge.  aethnography.  afieldwork.  afolklore.  ahidden self.  aimagination.  amagic.  amanifest.  amekeo.  anative peoples.  anatural context.  apapua new guinea.  areligion.  aritual.  asecret knowledge.  aself conceptualization.  aself knowledge.  aself reflection.  aselfhood.  asocial relations.  asorcery.  astudies in melanesian anthropology series.  asubjective imagery.  atribe.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052008829040uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520915275?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520915275423Coveruhttps:/